occurrences.line_text: He turnd himselfe into a fruitfull vine,
And into her faire bosome made his grapes decline.
But forward with bold steps into the next roome went.
Into the inner roome, from whence they first did rise.
Vnwares it strooke into her snowie chest,
The doubtfull current into diuers wayes:
Into this world, to worke confusion,
What time his people into partes did riue,
Which did her powre into three parts diuyde;
Eftsoones his life may passe into the next;
Then entred Cambell first into the list,
That through the mayles into his thigh it entred,
Pierst through his beuer quite into his brow,
Ne into ayre did vanish presently,
Ne chaunged was into a starre in sky:
Into his other brethren, that suruiued,
Streight entring into Triamond, him fild
And rushing forth into the emptie field,
Into his throate and life it pierced quight,
Now falne into their fellowship by chance,
Into the hunters toile, doth rage and rore,
Into the thickest of that knightly preasse
Into an heard, farre from the husband farme,
Into the Martian field adowne descended,
That sudden newes had made into his spright;
Streight into griefe, that her deare hart nigh swelt,
And eft gan into tender teares to melt.
She almost fell againe into a swound,
The heauens abhorre, and into darkenesse driue.
Since I was brought into this dolefull den;
Thine honor sau'd, though into thraldome throwne?
Thence forth she past into his dreadfull den,
Saluting him, gan into speach to fall,
Till that at length into that forrest wide,
Into the lookers hart, and killeth farre away.
His soule descended downe into the Stygian reame.
Of many Nations into thraldome led,
From his false eyes, into their harts and parts entire.
Should wilfully be into thraldome brought,
Exchanged out of one into an other feare.
In case his burning lust should breake into excesse.
And thrusting fierce into the thickest preace,
Cast into sundry shapes by wondrous skill,
Into the inmost Temple thus I came,
Her threw into a dongeon deepe and blind,
Into old Gall, that now is cleeped France,
Into his waters, as he passeth downe,
Into his mouth his maystring bridle threw,
Into some pit, where she him heares complaine,
Who now was falne into new languishment
Are now transformed into hardest stone:
They into that ere long will be degendered.
For who so list into the heauens looke,
Into the great Nemoean lions groue.
Into redoubted perill forth did call;
Into all filth and foule iniquitie,
Into a caue from companie exilde,
Into the which whomso he ouerthrowes,
Leapes forth into the floud, and there assaies
Into the floud: streight leapt the Carle vnblest,
In vaine loud crying, and into the flood
I will thrust downe into the deepest maine,
By all that dying into it doe fade.
Doe flourish now, they into dust shall vade.
So he the words into his ballaunce threw,
So first the right he put into one scale;
Appear'd in heauen, into the field they came,
Sir Artegall into the Tilt-yard came,
Fayre Florimell, into the common hall,
Th'enchaunted Damzell vanisht into nought:
And into nothing goe, ere one could it bewray.
Into the Sea her selfe did headlong throw,
Came forth into the rout, and them t'array began.
So forth into the field she marched thence,
Into a long large chamber, which was sield
Through slipperie footing, fell into the brooke,
Did cast for to allure, into her trap to fall.
Into her eye, which th'heart mote haue relieued,
Into a lower roome, and by and by
Into the riuer, where he drunke his deadly last.
Was thence by them into the Temple led;
Into her pregnant bosome, forth she brought
Into outragious flames vnwares did grow,
And forth into the lower parts did pas;
Fled fast into the towne, and her sole victor left.
She entred into all the partes entire.
Thenceforth she streight into a bowre him brought,
Not onely into bitter termes forth brust,
Into a Tygre, and that Tygres scath
Into a Foxe himselfe he first did tourne;
Into a bird it chaung'd, and from him past,
Into a Hedgehogge all vnwares it went,
And bringing light into the heauens fayre,
And into moores and marshes banisht had,
Into the field their Tyrants Seneschall.
Into the Princes shield, where it empight;
Into his shield it readie passage found,
And ran into the Hall, where he did weene
Thenceforth into that Castle he her led,
Gan into one assemble all the might
Fallen into that Tyrants hand and vsage bad.
For ye into like thraldome me did throw,
Into the sea he droue quite from that soyle,
Talus into the sea did forth issew,
Into the field, as if he fearelesse were,
That many wounds into his flesh it made,
How they might make him into mischiefe fall,
Into the mindes of mortall men doe well,
And goodly fury into them infuse;
Into the rest, which round about you ring,
That you into such perils presently doth call?
Into this wicked world he forth was sent,
Into this bay of perill and disgrace?
Thence passing forth, into the hall he came,
Her foe deliuer vp into her hand:
Into the life of his malignant foe;
Into his hart, and had so sternely wroke
Into the couert did her selfe withdraw,
He burst into these words, as to him seemed good.
Into some forrein land, where as no need
Into the land of Faerie, where no wight
Into this land, where I haue wond thus long,
Yet when she fled into that couert greaue,
Into his wounds, him vp thereon did reare,
Into the wood was bearing her apace
And carelesly into the riuer goth,
And running streight into the thickest wood,
The iuyce whereof into his wound he wrought,
Into his gaping throte, that made him grone
To leape into the same after our liues end.
Went forth streightway into the forrest wyde,
Vnwares into the daunger of defame.
They fled, and fast into the wood did get:
She fell into that saluage villaines hand,
He thence them led into his Hermitage,
So taking them apart into his cell,
Ne stayd, till that he came into the hall:
Into his Lords forbidden hall to passe.
The which was fall'n into this feeble case,
At last he vp into the chamber came,
The tempred steele did not into his braynepan byte.
Into the chamber, where that Dame remayned
Into her trap vnto their owne decay:
Deliuered hath into your hands by gift;
Fell into wretched woes, which she repented late.
That for her sake fell into misery:
Into their neighbours borders; ne did giue
With that he thrusts into the thickest throng,
And from the townes into the countrie forsed,
From thence into the open fields he fled,
[I]nto captiuity.
He durst not enter into th'open greene,
Into this place was brought, and kept with gard
Looking each houre into deathes mouth to fall,
With which he forth went into th'open light:
Into their caues, their heads from death to hide,
This doen, into those theeuish dens he went,
But now I come into my course againe,
Into the emptie fields, where liuing wight
Into their comely tresses dewly drest,
For passing ioy, which did all into pitty melt.
At length into a Monastere did light,
Into their cloysters now he broken had,
And them pursu'd into their dortours sad,
From thence into the sacred Church he broke,
And got into the world at liberty againe.
Into like bands, ne maystred any more:
Yet none of them could euer bring him into band.
And bring into a mighty Peres displeasure,
But to auoyde th'intollerable stowre,
For through his traines he her intrapped hath,
Could hardly him intreat, to tell his griefe:
No solace could her Paramour intreat,
That Saxon kings his friendship shall intreat;
In those old times, of which I doe intreat,
Strangers no more so rudely to intreat,
She then began them humbly to intreate,
With humble prayers and intreatfull teares;
For no intreatie would forgoe so glorious spoyle.
And wooe with faire intreatie, to disclose,
The more that he with meeke intreatie prayd,
Vpon her knee, intreating him for grace,
But wofull Ladie let me you intrete,
Their clasping armes, in wanton wreathings intricate.
Deepe Indus, and Maeander intricate,
In which her royall presence is introld;
And after hauing searcht the intuse deepe,
With fire and sword the region to inuade;
Yet he it oft aduentur'd to inuade.
Now forst to yield, now forcing to inuade,
The shame and death, which will thee soone inuade?
And cleauing the hard steele, did deepe inuade
Gan more the same frequent, and further to inuade.
Then gan the Hunnes and Picts inuade this land,
Least that his Lord they should behind inuade;
With which he wonts the Stygian realmes inuade,
That neuer foes his kingdome might inuade,
The powre of forrein Paynims, which inuade thy land.
Now blazed was, and feare did all inuade,
Becomes a bodie, and doth then inuade
To shrowd themselues, whiles sleepe their senses did inuade.
Nor seeme too suddeinly him to inuade:
Battell against the Gods? so we a God inuade.
And brushing his faire brest, did her inuade;
With th'one his foes he threatned to inuade,
Those be vnquiet thoughts, that carefull minds inuade.
Whom without perill he cannot inuade.
With which in case thou canst him not inuade,
The gentle Aladine did earst inuade,
Out of their ambush broke, and gan him to inuade.
The dwelling of these shepheards did inuade,
Whom Coridon him counseld to inuade
This land inuaded with like violence,
By a strong Tyrant, who inuaded has
And wall'd by nature gainst inuaders wrong,
Inueigled him to follow her desires vnmeete.
If Bacchus merry fruit they did inuent,
She could deuise, and thousand waies inuent,
Till him aliue or dead she did inuent.
Fie on the man, that did it first inuent,
At last when as no meanes he could inuent,
And bad his seruant Talus to inuent
Well therefore did the antique world inuent,
Or doen she heard, she would streightwayes inuent,
And fouly rayle, with all she could inuent;
By all the courteous meanes he could inuent;
The villaine stayd not aunswer to inuent,
With all kind courtesies, he could inuent;
Such as that prudent Romane well inuented,
Therefore the antique wisards well inuented,
Ay me, that euer guyle in wemen was inuented.
Cannot find one this girdle to inuest.
And bound them with inuiolable bands;
But to preserue inuiolated right,
Him to inuite vnto his simple home;
So after Nilus invndation,
He was invulnerable made by Magicke leare.
With footing worne, and leading inward farre:
The caruer Holme, the Maple seeldom inward sound.
And wast his inward gall with deepe despight,
Yet still he stroue to cloke his inward bale,
Inward corruption, and infected sin,
With heat, toyle, wounds, armes, smart, & inward fire
Through inward feare, and seeming pale and faint
His stout courage to stoupe, and shew his inward paine.
Mammon emmoued was with inward wrath;
And inward griefe, he fiercely gan approch,
And stared ghastly, some for inward shame,
And by long triall of the inward griefe,
That from like inward fire that outward smoke had steemd.
But yet her wound still inward freshly bled,
His inward parts, and all his entrayles wast,
The inward smoke, that did before but steeme,
His inward griefe, by meanes to him well knowne,
Shewing desire her inward flame to slake:
Twixt inward doole and felonous despight;
Long thus he chawd the cud of inward griefe,
Dying each day with inward wounds of dolours dart.
Was thrild with inward griefe, as when in chace
But if through inward griefe or wilfull scorne
T'expresse the meaning of the inward mind,
From inward parts, with cancred malice lind,
And inward grudge fild his heroicke brest:
That none mote haue accesse, nor inward fare,
In generation seeke to quench their inward fire.
That he did languish of some inward thought,
Who reading it with inward loathfulnesse,
Her inward brest, and in her entrayles fryde,
Chawing the cud of griefe and inward paine,
By outward shew her inward sence defining.
With inward griefe and malice did against them swell.
Her flesh for felnesse, which she inward hid:
And not in outward shows, but inward thoughts defynd.
With hearts dismay and inward dolour queld,
Her stubborne hart with inward deepe effect,
Burning with inward rancour and despight,
With that he sighed deepe for inward tyne:
And ranckling inward with vnruly stounds,
For all that shame, which kindled inward hate.
So inward shame of her vncomely case
But inwardly he chawed his owne maw
Disarmd, disgrast, and inwardly dismayde,
Mournes inwardly, and makes to himselfe mone:
Ranckled so sore, and festred inwardly,
Whereof she seemes ashamed inwardly.
And flam'd with zeale of vengeance inwardly,
Grieu'd to the soule, and groning inwardly,
That his great hart gan inwardly to swell
With great admiraunce inwardly was moued,
He deepely sigh't, and groaned inwardly,
His heart with vengeaunce inwardly did swell,
Which could redresse, for it was inwardly vnsound.
Hymen iO Hymen, dauncing all around,
And next to him Iocante did ensew;
Sans foy: full large of limbe and euery ioint
How for Iolas sake he did apply
Triumphing in great ioy and iolity;
Her mate he was a iollie youthfull knight,
And left him now as sad, as whilome iollie,
To feede her foolish humour, and vaine iolliment.
Sate with a knight in ioyous iolliment
Of which some seemd with liuely iollitee,
For on a day prickt forth with iollitie
Now gan his hart all swell in iollitie,
And did of ioy and iollitie deuize,
In loues and gentle iollities arrayd,
That night they pas in ioy and iollity,
Did shake, and seem'd to daunce for iollity,
The whiles one sung a song of loue and iollity.
Ay caroling of loue and iollity,
That much Malbecco ioyed in his iollity.
Full iolly knight he seemd, and faire did sitt,
Full iolly knight he seemde, and well addrest,
Hippolytus a iolly huntsman was,
Now strike your sailes ye iolly Mariners,
A iolly yeoman, Marshall of the same,
Courted of many a iolly Paramoure,
A iolly person, and of comely vew;
The iolly Paridell, for all his paine.
The iolly Satyres full of fresh delight,
But chose emongst the iolly Satyres still to wonne.
After whom marcht a iolly company,
Amongst the rest there was a iolly knight,
But he their sonne full fresh and iolly was,
He chaunst to come whereas a iolly Knight,
Now turne againe my teme thou iolly swayne,
She was to weete that iolly Shepheards lasse,
That iolly shepheard, which there piped, was
Pype iolly shepheard, pype thou now apace
Haile iolly shepheard, which thy ioyous dayes
Despoyled of those ioyes and iollyhead,
For goodly triumph and great iollyment,
Trew Ionathan, and Dauid trustie tryde;
Both Silo this, and Iordan did excell,
Hither came Ioseph of Arimathy,
That soone in him was left no one corrupted iot.
And thou most dreaded impe of highest Ioue,
And angry Ioue an hideous storme of raine
And thundring Ioue, that high in heauen doth dwell,
Or if that any else did Ioue excell:
More old then Ioue, whom thou at first didst breede,
Cursing high Ioue, the which them thither sent.
When Ioue auizd, that could the dead reuiue,
The wrath of thundring Ioue, that rules both night and day?
O lightsome day, the lampe of highest Ioue,
As when almightie Ioue in wrathfull mood,
That dedicated is t'Olympicke Ioue,
Ne swelling Neptune, ne loud thundring Ioue
Of whom high Ioue wont whylome feasted bee,
Accusing highest Ioue and gods ingrate,
And triumphes of PhlegrÃ¦an Ioue he wrote,
His worke, for which he was by Ioue depriued
By this th'eternall lampes, wherewith high Ioue
Ioue laught on Venus from his soueraigne see,
To scorne the ioy, that Ioue is glad to seeke;
To scale the skyes, and put Ioue from his right:
Therein was writ, how often thundring Ioue
Whiles thus on earth great Ioue these pageaunts playd,
And take me for their Ioue, whiles Ioue to earth is gone.
And take me for their Ioue, whiles Ioue to earth is gone.
Whom Ioue did loue, and chose his cup to beare,
Well worthie thou to be of Ioue accurst,
Not all the gods can chaunge, nor Ioue him self can free.
As Ioue will haue aduaunced to the skie,
Throwne out by angry Ioue in his vengeance,
Helpe therefore, O thou sacred imp of Ioue,
So hardly butted those two twinnes of Ioue,
Well prou'd in that same day, when Ioue those Gyants quelled.
With which thou canst euen Ioue himselfe to loue entise.
Of highest Ioue, who doth true iustice deale
And ioyous light the house of Ioue forsooke:
By thundring Ioue in the Phlegrean plaine.
All louely daughters of high Ioue, that hight,
They are the daughters of sky-ruling Ioue,
To Ioues high house through heauens bras-paued way
That shyning lampes in Ioues high house were light:
Which fast is tyde to Ioues eternall seat?
That now I weene Ioues dreaded thunder light
As when Ioues harnesse-bearing Bird from hie
To light their blessed lamps in Ioues eternall hous.
Frame thunderbolts for Ioues auengefull threate.
When to Ioues pallace she doth take her way;
Of th'Oceans seede, but Ioues and Phoebus kinde;
In Ioues eternall house, vnwist of wight,
Vpon Ioues iudgement seat wayt day and night,
Thereto the Heauens alwayes Iouiall,
Whiles from their iournall labours they did rest,
All woxen weary of their iournall toyle:
And on their former iourney forward pas,
Who told her all that fell in iourney as she went.
Alreadie harnessed for iourney new;
Whiles on her wearie iourney she did ride;
So parted we and on our iourney driue,
Vnto the iourney which he had behight:
And to his purposd iourney him prepar'd:
And draw from on this iourney to proceede.
As lay her iourney, through that perlous Pace,
They tooke their steeds, & forth vpo[n] their iourney went.
T'abridg their iourney long, and lingring day;
Then he forth on his iourney did proceede,
She forth issewed, and on her iourney went;
Vprose, forth on their iourney for to wend:
One may his iourney bring too soone to euill end.
And did themselues vnto their iourney dight.
But leauing him forth on his iourney far'd:
Which done, vnto his former iourney he retourned.
Himselfe vnto his iourney gan prepare,
And to his former iourney him addrest,
That she her selfe had to the iourney dight,
To make there lenger stay, forth on his iourney goth.
Vnto their iourney; but that Squire and Dame
Must landed be, now at her iourneyes end:
Yet nought the nearer to his iourneys end;
Bathed in wanton blis and wicked ioy:
Them both together laid, to ioy in vaine delight.
Of one bad sire, whose youngest is Sans ioy,
The fire of loue and ioy of cheualree
Such ioy made Vna, when her knight she found;
Showting for ioy, and still before their way
Was writ Sans ioy, they new arriued find:
That night they pas in ioy and iollity,
Ah deare Sans ioy, next dearest to Sans foy,
Cause of my new griefe, cause of my new ioy,
To ioy at his foole-happie ouersight:
So doubly is distrest twixt ioy and cares
For griefe whereof the lad n'ould after ioy,
Who had more ioy to raunge the forrest wyde,
Such ioy he had, their stubborne harts to quell,
Ah Satyrane, my dearling, and my ioy,
That him of life, and vs of ioy hath reft?
What worlds delight, or ioy of liuing speach
With hasty ioy: to see him made her glad,
Ensample make of him your haplesse ioy,
Whose onely ioy was to relieue the needes
Her hart with ioy vnwonted inly sweld,
And greatly ioy each other well to see:
And bid her ioy of that her happie brood;
And with great ioy into that Citie wend,
betrouthed is with ioy:
Vprose with hastie ioy, and feeble speed
Proclaymed ioy and peace through all his state;
Of their new ioy, and happie victorie
Great ioy was made that day of young and old,
Yet swimming in that sea of blisfull ioy,
Ioy may you haue, and euerlasting fame,
Is this the ioy of armes? be these the parts
Who in her loosenesse tooke exceeding ioy;
Did shew her selfe in great triumphant ioy,
And did of ioy and iollitie deuize,
Of his departure thence; for of her ioy
I long haue lackt, I ioy thy face to vew;
Some song in sweet consort, some laught for ioy,
Ioy thereof haue thou and eternall blis.
Both loue and louer, without hope of ioy,
He liues, but takes small ioy of his renowne;
And left her blisfull bowre of ioy aboue,
To scorne the ioy, that Ioue is glad to seeke;
He comes not here, we scorne his foolish ioy,
There now he liues in euerlasting ioy,
For she does ioy to play emongst her peares,
Depriu'd of kindly ioy and naturall delight.
Whom for remembraunce of her passed ioy,
The God of his desire, the ioy of misers blind.
For passing ioy, which so great maruaile brings,
Triumphing in great ioy and iolity;
I ioy to see you lout so low on ground,
For sudden ioy, and secret feare withall,
In these wild woods, as was her wonted ioy,
With one sterne looke so daunted, that no ioy
For all his ioy, he said, in that distresse
And for more ioy, that captiue Lady faire
To bath in ioy and amorous desire,
The ioy of Gods and men, that vnder skie
And so well skild; nathlesse he takes great ioy
Ioy on those warlike women, which so long
And all the raging seas for ioy forgot to rore.
Ioy to you both, ye double noursery
And ioy likewise this solemne day to see?
But ioy that for his sake I suffer prisonment.
To tast of ioy, and to wont pleasures to retourne.
And when as he him nam'd, for ioy he brake
Timely to ioy, and carrie comely cheare.
They shouted all for ioy of his successe,
And take great ioy to publish it to many,
Onely the vse of armes, which most I ioy,
Thou brings? aie me, is this the timely ioy,
For ioy of such good hap by heauenly grace.
The fruite of ioy and blisse, though long time dearely bought.
And wondrous ioy felt in her spirits thrall:
So full of ioy, streight forth she ran in hast
In her owne breast, this mothers ioy descriue:
For passing ioy, which did all into pitty melt.
Who ioyning ioy with her in one accord,
There leaue we them in ioy, and let vs tell
As for great ioyance of his newcome guest.
She chearefull fresh and full of ioyance glad,
And made full goodly ioyance to her new found mate.
There with great ioyance and with gladsome glee,
That in this ioyous place they mote haue ioyance free.
So blesse thee God, and giue thee ioyance of thy dreame
